  <h1>Non-Economic Damages in Wrongful Death</h1>
  <p class="byline">By Ellis Pemberton, Editor-in-Chief. Reviewed May 2026.</p>

  <p>Non-economic damages compensate survivors for the loss of relationship that is, on any honest accounting, the larger harm a wrongful death causes. The numbers are inherently subjective, vary widely by jurisdiction, and are increasingly subject to statutory caps. This guide explains what's typically recoverable and where caps apply.</p>

  <h2>The categories</h2>

  <h3>Loss of consortium</h3>
  <p>Loss of the marital relationship for the surviving spouse: companionship, intimacy, comfort, society, support. Recoverable in every state for a surviving spouse, though the label varies (some call it "loss of consortium," some "loss of society," some break it into sub-categories).</p>

  <h3>Loss of parental companionship and guidance</h3>
  <p>For surviving minor children, the loss of the parent's ongoing relationship: companionship, guidance, training, instruction, moral and intellectual development. Recoverable in most states for minor children. Adult children may recover this category in some states; in others their share is reduced or eliminated.</p>

  <h3>Loss of filial consortium</h3>
  <p>Less commonly recognized. The mirror image: parents' loss of an adult or minor child's relationship. Recognized in some states (Massachusetts, others), not in others.</p>

  <h3>Mental anguish of survivors</h3>
  <p>The emotional pain of the survivors at the loss. Some states fold this into loss of consortium / companionship; others recognize it as a separate damage category. Where separate, it is recoverable independently and not subsumed in the relationship-loss damages.</p>

  <h3>Loss of inheritance</h3>
  <p>In some states, survivors may recover the value of inheritance that would have been received had the decedent lived. This overlaps with lost earnings (the decedent's earnings that would have accumulated as savings and ultimately been inherited). Recognition varies.</p>

  <h2>How non-economic damages are valued</h2>
  <p>Non-economic damages are inherently subjective. There is no formula or appraisal method. Practical valuation approaches:</p>

  <h3>Multiplier method</h3>
  <p>The most common approach in settlement: apply a multiplier (typically 1&times; to 5&times;) to the economic damages. The multiplier reflects the breadth and severity of the non-economic loss. Death of a young parent of minor children: high multiplier. Death of an older retiree with adult independent children: lower multiplier.</p>

  <h3>Per-diem method</h3>
  <p>Calculate a daily value (often a per-day equivalent of the decedent's pre-death earnings, or simply a chosen rate) and multiply by the survivor's remaining life expectancy. Less common in modern practice; produces high numbers that defense uses to argue the method is arbitrary.</p>

  <h3>Comparable case method</h3>
  <p>Reference jury verdicts in similar fact patterns in the relevant jurisdiction. Verdict reporters and trial-attorney associations maintain databases. Useful for setting expectations but not for setting a defensible final number.</p>

  <h2>State variation</h2>

  <p>Three structural patterns matter:</p>

  <h3>States that allow broad non-economic recovery (majority)</h3>
  <p>Most states allow recovery for loss of consortium, parental companionship, and mental anguish. The multiplier method is the practical mechanism for settlement.</p>

  <h3>States with statutory caps</h3>
  <p>Many states have capped non-economic damages, particularly in medical malpractice deaths. Examples:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>California (MICRA, medical malpractice only):</strong> $350K cap (recently increased on a phased schedule).</li>
    <li><strong>Texas (medical malpractice):</strong> $250K per defendant in non-economic damages.</li>
    <li><strong>Colorado:</strong> $250K general cap on non-economic damages, with adjustments and exceptions.</li>
    <li><strong>Kansas:</strong> Capped at $325K (rising on schedule).</li>
    <li><strong>Maryland:</strong> Capped at increasing amounts ($890K+ in 2026).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Caps in non-medical-malpractice wrongful death exist in some states but are less common. Many caps have been challenged on state constitutional grounds; outcomes vary.</p>

  <h3>States with limited non-economic recovery</h3>
  <p>A small number of states historically limited non-economic recovery more aggressively. Practice varies; specifics need to be checked for the relevant state.</p>

  <h2>What moves the multiplier up or down</h2>

  <h3>Up</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Young decedent with surviving young children.</li>
    <li>Decedent who was a primary caregiver, primary breadwinner, or both.</li>
    <li>Catastrophic survival (prolonged conscious dying) increases pre-death pain-and-suffering category.</li>
    <li>Defendant misconduct that supports punitive damages also tends to support higher compensatory multipliers.</li>
    <li>Strong evidence of plaintiff sympathy (good photographs, witness testimony to decedent's character, evidence of family closeness).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Down</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Older decedent at the end of work life.</li>
    <li>Estranged family relationships (defense will probe for estrangement, divorce filings, geographic separation).</li>
    <li>Lack of dependent children.</li>
    <li>Disputed liability.</li>
    <li>Plaintiff fault attribution (in comparative fault states).</li>
    <li>Pre-existing illness or condition arguably affecting life expectancy.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Punitive damages (separate category)</h2>
  <p>Where the conduct was reckless, intentional, or showed conscious disregard for safety, punitive damages may be available. Punitive damages punish the defendant rather than compensate the survivors. They are not subject to the personal-consumption deduction or to most state caps that apply to compensatory non-economic damages, though many states have separate punitive-damage caps (often a multiplier of compensatory damages, or a hard dollar cap).</p>

  <p>Punitive damages can substantially exceed compensatory damages in egregious cases. Drunk driver fatalities, repeated FMCSA violations in trucking deaths, product manufacturers with knowledge of defects, hospitals with patterns of negligent supervision &mdash; these are typical punitive-damages cases.</p>

  <h2>Tax treatment</h2>
  <p>Federal income tax excludes from gross income compensatory damages received "on account of personal physical injuries or physical sickness." This excludes the lost-earnings, medical, pain-and-suffering, and consortium components of a wrongful death recovery. Punitive damages are taxable. Interest on a judgment is taxable. State tax treatment generally follows federal. Allocation of settlement proceeds among damage categories can affect tax outcomes; structure settlements with an attorney and CPA's input.</p>

  <p>For economic damages, see <a href="/guides/economic-damages-in-wrongful-death-cases">economic damages</a>. For standing to bring the claim, see <a href="/guides/who-can-file-a-wrongful-death-claim">who can file</a>.</p>
